04740nam a22005055i 9780226027494DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20121992ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226027494  a(DE-B1597)524635  a(OCoLC)1045799794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDG678.24.F73 ǂb R67 1992eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a945/.3107/092aB1 aRosenthal, Margaret F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Honest Courtesan :bVeronica Franco, Citizen and Writer in Sixteenth-Century Venice /cMargaret F. Rosenthal. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2012] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b31 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWomen in Culture and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Satirizing the Courtesan: Franco's Enemies -- tTwo. Fashioning the Honest Courtesan: Franco's Patrons -- tThree. Addressing Venice: Franco's Familiar Letters -- tFour. Denouncing the Courtesan: Franco's Inquisition Trial and Poetic Debate -- tFive. The Courtesan in Exile: An Elegiac Future -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Venetian courtesan has long captured the imagination as a female symbol of sexual license, elegance, beauty, and unruliness. What then to make of the cortigiana onesta—the honest courtesan who recast virtue as intellectual integrity and offered wit and refinement in return for patronage and a place in public life? Veronica Franco (1546-1591) was such a woman, a writer and citizen of Venice, whose published poems and familiar letters offer rich testimony to the complexity of the honest courtesan's position. Margaret F. Rosenthal draws a compelling portrait of Veronica Franco in her cultural social, and economic world. Rosenthal reveals in Franco's writing a passionate support of defenseless women, strong convictions about inequality, and, in the eroticized language of her epistolary verses, the seductive political nature of all poetic contests. It is Veronica Franco's insight into the power conflicts between men and women—and her awareness of the threat she posed to her male contemporaries—that makes her literary works and her dealings with Venetian intellectuals so pertinent today. Combining the resources of biography, history, literary theory, and cultural criticism, this sophisticated interdisciplinary work presents an eloquent and often moving account of one woman's life as an act of self-creation and as a complex response to social forces and cultural conditions. "A book . . . pleasurably redolent of Venice in the 16th-century. Rosenthal gives a vivid sense of a world of salons and coteries, of intricate networks of family and patronage, and of literary exchanges both intellectual and erotic."—Helen Hackett, Times Higher Education Supplement The Honest Courtesan is the basis for the film Dangerous Beauty (1998) directed by Marshall Herskovitz. (The film was re-titled The Honest Courtesan for release in the UK and Europe in 1999.)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  avenice, italy, courtesan, sex work, prostitution, mistress, sexuality, femininity, elegance, cortigiana onesta, veronica franco, demi monde, virtue, patronage, public sphere, letters, citizenship, authorship, biography, history, book to film, adaptation, inquisition, trial, nonfiction, women, 16th century, dangerous beauty, gender, feminism, patriarchy.1 aStimpson, Catharine R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www